{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2abbott_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280604604/1945100101/0007.xml":{"full_text":"Weather Forecast\nei,*>M|a.nie Tf SteS\nTemperatures\u2014High, 68; low, 67, at A 2*41 Article* -A-# Sport* A-tt-18\n1:18 a.m. Yesterday\u2014High, 59, at Finance .A-16 Where to GO---J*-\u00ae\n12:01 a.m.; low, 54, at 7:01 am. W Lost and Pound, A-3 Woman\u2019* Page, B-19\n/-STTia ills City Home Delivery. Dally and Sunday ar PTrYTS\n93d YEAR. No. 37,039. Phone NA. 5000. iGES. so. v***. wa\u00abn s Sunday*. $i.oo\nVinson Proposes\n$5,000,000,000\nCut in Taxes\nIncome Levy Slash\nOf 3% Would Relieve\n12 Million of Returns\nBy J. A. O\u2019LEARY.\nA three-point program to cut\ntaxes by $5,000,000,000 in 1946\nwas laid before the House Ways\nand Means Committee today by\nSecretary of the Treasury Vin\nson.\nIt called for:\n1. Repeal of the 3 per .cent normal\ntax, effective January 1, to take be\ntween 10 and 12 million low-bracket\nindividuals off the tax rolls. The\nrevenue reduction would total $2,\n085,600,000.\n2. Repeal of the 95 per cent excess\nprofits tax on corporations, a reduc\ntion of $2,555,000,000.\n3. Fixing July 1, 1946, as the expi\nration date for wartime excise taxes\non such items as cosmetics, furs and\njewelry, which would otherwise con\ntinue until six months after the end\nof hostilities is declared, an indefi\nnite period. This would knock an\nother $547,000,000 off Treasury re\nceipts next year.\nNet Reduction 5 Billion.\nWhile these steps would aggregate\n$5,187,000,000, Mr. Vinson pointed out\nthat an increased volume of business\nactivity and spending resulting from\nthe tax relief would increase other\ntax collections enough to make the\nnet loss in revenue not more than\n$5,000,000,000.\nSecretary Vinson took note of the\nfact that Congress also faces a de\ncision on whether to let the payroll\ntax for old-age insurance go up\nautomatically on January 1 from 1\nper cent to 2% per cent each on\nemployer and employe, the effect or\nwhich would be to cancel out a good\npart of the general tax relief about\nto be given individuals and business.\nOn this subject, the Secretary\ncontented himself with a recom\nmendation that \u201crevision of pay\nroll tax rates should wait to be\nmade part of the broader action\non social security financing as a\nwhole.\u201d He had reference to bills\nCongress will consider early next\nyear to put in the broader cradle\nto-grave social security program.\nGOP Seeks 20 Per Cent Cut.\nAs the Treasury head read a long\nprepared statement to the commit\ntee in closed session. Republicans\nwere making plans to fight for an\nalternative program that would give\nall individuals a flat 20 per cent\ntax cut across the board.\nIn a separate report made pub\nlic today, War Mobilization Director\nSnyder indorsed the main features\nof the Vinson tax program. Most\nof Mr. Vinson's carefully prepared\ndocument painted a word picture of\nthe many heavy obligations still\nfacing the Federal Government as\nan aftermath of'the war, which, he\nwarned, make it unwise for Congress\nto go any further than he is recom\nmending now in slashing taxes for\nnext year.\nHe reminded the law makers that\neven if no reduction is made in\nrates, the decline in payrolls and\nbusiness profits resulting from the\nend of the war would cut the tax\nyield by $9,000,000,000 below the\npeak of war collections.\nMust Reckon Impact.\n\u201cThe taxpayer will not feel any\nrelief from that drop in tax liabili\nties, but the Government must\nreckon with its impact on revenue\nreceipts,\u201d Mr. Vinson pointed out.\nIn recommending that the bulk\nof the individual tax relief be given\nthose in the low brackets by repeal\nof the 3 per cent normal tax, Mr.\nVinson testified:\n\u201cThe normal tax imposes income\ntax on about 12,000.000 families\nwhich are exempt from the surtax.\nThus, a family composed of a man,\nhis wife and one child has three\nsurtax exemptions of $500 each and\nis thus exempt from surtax on net\nincome up to $1,500. The normal tax,\nhowever, applies on all net income\nabove $500 for each income receiver\nwithout regard to family status or\nnumber of dependents. Accordingly,\nfnmilv nov rtArmol to V\nof 3 per cent on all income above\n$500.\nThe amounts of tax are relatively\nsmall from the viewpoint of the\nGovernment and, accordingly, rela\ntively expensive to collect, both\nthrough withholding and through\n(See TAXES, Page A^Tj\nJed Johnson Declines\nCourt Appointment\nE> the Associated Press.\nRepreslntative Jed Johnson,\nDemocrat, of Oklahoma, will retain\nhis seat in Congress instead of ac\ncepting an appointment to the Cus\ntoms Court, to which he was ap\npointed by the late President\nRoosevelt.\nHis nomination was confirmed by\nthe Senate last spring, but Mr.\nJohnson announced later he\nplanned to serve out his present\nterm in the House and might be a\ncandidate for renomination.\nHe made public today corre\nspondence in which President Tru\nman asked him to remain in Con\ngress, and the Oklahoman said he\nhad \u201cdecided to accede to your\nwishes.\u201d\nIn his letter to Mr. Johnson, dated\nAugust 29, the President said:\n\u201cOf course, I want' you to do what\never is best for Jed Johnson but, it\nis my opinion, the welfare of the\ncountry would be promoted if you\nstayed in the House of Representa\ntives.\n\"Your position on the Appropria\ntions' Committee is a most impor\ntant one\u2014you are familiar with the\nprocedure in the House and I feel\nthat it would be a loss to the country\nif you decide to retire from this\nbranch of public service.\u201d\nMr. Johnson, in a letter dated Sep\ntember 25, said, in part:\n\u201cI have thought the matter over\ncarefully and prayerfully and have\ndefinitely and cheerfully decided to\naccede to your wishes, which I as\nsure you are my wishes also\nD. C. General Feted by Japanese\nIn Hiroshima Atom Bomb Probe\n_ ___\nTakes hot Bath in\nTiled Pit Before\nSumptuous Banquet\nBy WILLIAM H. SHIPPEN, JR.,\nStar Stall Correspondent.\nTOKYO, Oct. 1.\u2014The atomic\nbomb mission now preparing to\nfly back to Washington received\ncordial co-operation of all classes\nof Japanese, especially around\nHiroshima and Nagasaki.\nBrig. Gen. James B. Newman of\nWashington was prepared for almost\nanything but smiling hospitality\nwhen he and his experts arrived at\nthe scene of history\u2019s biggest man\nmade disaster.\nThe general, whose wife is the\nformer Prances M. (Robbie) Robin\nson, personal assistant to the late\nHugh Johnson, head of NRA, had\ncome to this theater from service\nin Htirope and you could have\nbowled him over with a couple of\nchopsticks, let alone a ceremonial\ndinner.\nNot so much as a hard look\ndid the investigators get, except from\nthe ramrod-like military command\ner, who broke down and brought\nRussians Reported\nRefusing to Sign\nBig 5 Agreements\nDemands of Molotov\nOn Balkans Believed\nCause of New Tangle\nBy the Associated Press.\nLONDON, Oct. 1.\u2014The Coun\ncil of Foreign Ministers, still\nseeking a foundation for Eu\nrope\u2019s peace structure, made a\nlast-minute effort today to reach\nagreement after it was reported\nthat the Soviet Union had re\nfuse to sign conference docu\nments unless her Balkan treaty\ndemands were met.\nDelegates remained in session\nuntil after 1 a.m., debating the\nsame subject which has been argued\nfor more than a week\u2014Soviet For\neign Commissar V. M; Molotov\u2019s\ninsistence that only Britain, Russia\nand the United States be allowed\nto design the peace pacts with Ro\nmania, Bulgaria and Hungary. On\nChina's suggestion the council\nagreed to meet again later in the\n\u2018day.\nThe Russians based their insistent\ndemands on tjie Potsdam decision\nthat only nations which signed an\narmistice with the defeated Axis\nsatellites be permitted to write\nffAntioe wrifH fhACO nations\nChina and France, both members\nof the five-power council, were not\narmistice signatories.\nLast night\u2019s meeting, called to dis\ncuss final conference protocols and\na communique, broke up after the\ndelegates had spent 3% hours re\nstating their previous positions, in\nformed sources said.\nMore Talks Due Today.\nMore informal talks among the\nSoviet Union, the United States and\nBritain seemed likely before tonight.\nThere was speculation that the Rus\nsians might agree to sign conference\ndocuments to present an appearance\nof agreement even if an accord was\nnot reached on the Balkans.\nSo far as is known, no decision has\nbeen made on the time and place of\nthe next council meeting.\nWith the end of the conference\nimmiment, informed sources gave\nthese reasons for failure of the min\nisters to agree on major peace\nproblems:\n1. Lack of preparation and ad\nvance exchanges of views.\n2. The fact that three of the min\nisters\u2014Secretary of State Byrnes,\nBritish Foreign Secretary Ernest\nBevin and Chinese Foreign Minister\nWang Shin-chieh\u2014are new ap\npointees.\n3. What was described as Soviet\nsensitivity over publicity which pic\ntured the United States in a more\npowerful economic and military\nposition.\n4. Mutual suspicion.\n5. The varying interpretations of\nsuch words as \u201cdemocracy\u201d among\nthe powers.\nLeft Wing Extremist 'Coup\"\nf f r i\nin iwmuniu is reureu\nBUCHAREST, Sept. 27 (Delayed)\nf/P).\u2014Reports circulated in the Ro\nmanian capital today that if the\nLondon Council of Foreign Min\nisters adjourns without taking con\nclusive action on Romania, leftwing\nextremists may try to eliminate all\ntheir opposition.\nPolitical leaders opposing the ex\ntremists eagerly hope that the coun\ncil will yet reach an agreement per\nmitting formation of a government\nacceptable to the United States,\nGreat Britain and Russia.\nAmerican and British quarters\njoined with the leaders of the Na\ntional Peasant, Liberal and Socialist\nparties in emphasizing that post\nponement of a decision would be\nserious.\nUnofficially, both the British and\nAmericans say they favor formation\nof an interim cabinet of technicians,\nwhich would be politically neutral.\nThe main objective would be to pre\npare the nation for elections which\nwould give the parties representa\ntion in the government on the basis\nof an electoral count.\nKing Michael appears firm in his\ndetermination not to deal with the\npresent government of Premier\nPetru Groza, who has the support\nof Russia. That means that unless\nthe Groza government tries to take\nover royal prerogatives, no decree\npassed by the government can be\ncome law.\nIn an interview, Romania\u2019s minis\nter of propaganda, Constantinescu\nYashl, asserted the Groza govern\nment has the entire support of the\nnation, including the largest ele\nments of the National Peasant and\nLiberal parties.\nJ\nRussians Respectful\nOf U. S. Atomic Bomb\nAt Big Five Parley\nBy the Asaociated Press.\nLONDON. Oct. 1.\u2014The bar\ngaining power which the atomic\nbomb gave the United States at\nthe Council of Foreign Minis\nters is underlined by this story\ntold by a delegate.\nSoviet Foreign Commissar V.\nM. Molotov, at a dinner party,\nremarked that Secretary of\nState Byrnes \u201cdoesn\u2019t need to\npersuade anyone\u2014he just has\nto hold up a little bomb.\u201d\n\"Mr. Molotov never makes\njokes to be funny,\u201d the delegate\nadded.\nvisitors three cases of Japanese beer\nwhen he learned they had not come\nto accept his Samurai sword in sur\nrender.\nSquads of police lined the way,\neach joining the procession, until it\nreached the Japanese hotel in tri\numphant formation. Local digni\ntaries were on hand to receive the\nAmericans and to invite them to the\n(See SHIPPEN, Page A-3.)\nMcKeough Nomination\nRejected, 10-7, by\nSenate Committee\nMaritime Commission\nNominee Turned Down;\nFirst Truman Defeat\nBr the AssociateJ Vres*.\nPresident Truman\u2019s nomina\ntion of Raymond S. McKeough,\nformer Democratic House mem\nber from Illinois, to the Mari\ntime Commission was rejected\ntoday by the Senate Commerce\nCommittee by a 10-7 vote.\nIf the Senate follows the ma\njority report it will be the first such\naction on a nomination by Mr.\nTruman since he succeeded to the\npresidency.\nChairman Bailey told reporters\nafter the closed meeting he voted\nfor confirmation, \u2018but refused to\ndisclose how other members voted.\nNot Due to CIO Connections.\nSenator Bailey said the adverse\nreport was \u201cnot due to his (Mr.\nMcKeough\u2019s) connections\" with the\nCIO Political Action Committee, but\nasserted that it was \u201cdue to the\nintense rivalry among factions of\nseamen\u2019s unions.\u201d\nMr. Truman was upheld in another\nnomination today, however. The\nJudiciary Committee approved the\nnomination of Gov. J. Harold Mc\nGrath of Rhode Island to be Solici\ntor General. Chairman McCarran\nsaid the nomination will be taken up\nin the Senate Wednesday.\nMr MrTT^nnah onnaaHno Kofnro a\nCommerce Subcommittee more than\ntwo weeks ago, said he was the 1944\ndirector of the CIO-PAC in Illinois.\nWisconsin and Indiana in support of\nthe fourth-term campaign of former\nPresident Roosevelt.\nHe emphasized, however, that he'\nwas not a CIO member, that he was\nacting in the nature of an \u201cemploye\u201d\nand still was on the payroll.\nNo Question of Integrity.\nSenator Bailey said several mem\nbers of the committee, who had\nserved in the House with Mr. Mc\nKeough, said the nominee was \u201ca\nfine man\u201d and there was no question\nof his integrity.\nThe Commerce Committee, at a\nprevious session, declined to take\nany action and Senator Bailey, at\nthat time, said the President would\nbe given an opportunity to shed\n\"more light\u201d on the nomination.\nAsked today whether the Presi\ndent had ben advised of the situa\ntion, Senator Bailey said he had\nbeen, but refused to amplify. He\nadded that he expected a fight on\nthe Senate floor.\nWilliam Green, head of the Amer\nican Federation of Labor, has been\nopposing the nomination.\nDeath Toll of 39 May Rise\nIn Scottish Express Wreck\n(Picture on Page A-14.)\nBy the Associated Press.\nLONDON, Oct. 1.\u2014Rescue work\ners expressed fear today that bodies\nof additional victims may be. buried\nin the twisted wreckage of the Scot\ntish express, which was derailed 30\nmiles\u00bboutside London yesterday with\nknown casualties of 39 dead and 94\ninjured.\nThe express was nearing the end\nof its 450-mile overnight journey\nfrom Perth, Scotland, when the loco\nmotive jumped a switch and plunged\ndown a 20-foot embankment, drag\nging six passenger coaches with it.\nRescue crews labored all day yes\nterday and all night extricating dead\nand injured.\nAmericans Seek\nForeign Funds\nSeized by Japan\nSearch Is Begun After\nClosing of 21 Banks\nBy Gen. MacArthur\nBj the Associated Pres*.\nTOKYO, Oct. 1.\u2014American oc\ncupation authorities today be\ngan a search for untold millions\nof dollars in gold, silver and cur\nrency which Japan was believed\nto have taken from the lands it\noverran.\nThe search paralleled other in\nvestigations into imperialistic war\nfinancing, made possible through\nGen. MacArthur\u2019s seizure today of\n21 Government-controlled financial\ninstitutions in Tokyo and six other\nlarge cities, and the ousting of\ntheir officials.\nThe Bank of Japan, the nations\nlargest financial institution, one\nfourth of which was owned by the\nJapanese imperial household, was\nclosed by an order of the Allied\ncommand.\nDue to Reopen Tomorrow.\nIt will open tomorrow. Col. R. P.\nKramer, Gen. MacArthur\u2019s eco\nnomic and scientific chief, said. \u201cIf\nthe Japanese provide full co-opera\ntion\u201d in locating the assets of the\nseized institutions which had office\nspace in the Bank of Japan Build\ning.\nBank officers pleaded last night\nthat they had had insufficient time\nto produce the requested assets and\nrecords. They had received in\nstructions from the Finance Min\nistry earlier, however, to have the\nrequested material on hand by last\nnight.\nAmerican troops on guard around\nthe bank assured depositors, many\nof them women sobbing in fear that\nthey might lose their life savings,\nthat their funds were safe.\nTwo other banks closed by Gen.\nMacArthur\u2014the Yokohama Species\nBank and the Hypotec\u2014re-opened\ntoday with Allied permission after\na check of their records.\nAllied headquarters said no trace\nwas found in the three institutions\nof \"hard money\" removed from the\nPhilippines and the Netherlands\nIndies during the Japanese occu\npation.\nSeme gold and gold stocks ear\nmarked for Siam and Indo-China,\nand some gold set aside for the Fed\neral Reserve Bank of North China\nwere reported found in the Bank of\nJapan.\nThe hunt for the missing funds\nthat once belonged to the Philip\npines, China and other nations be\ngan with a conference of Col.\nKramer and Viscount Keizo Shibu\nsawa, governor of the Bank of\nJapan, and other leading Japanese\nfinancial figures.\nDeny Holding Foreign Money.\nThe Japanese denied the Bank of\nJapan held any foreign money, de\nnied any knowledge. of a possible\nhiding place and maintained they\nhart nn control over financial act.iv\nitles of field military commanders.\nThe militarists, the bankers said,\nhad the power either to sell their\nlooted assets aVid place the money\nin- a special disbursement fund of\nthe finance ministry or \u201ckeep the\nassets for themselves.\"\nShibusawa declared he knew\nnothing of reported transfers of gold\nand currency from the Philippines\nto Japan.\nThe bankers gave Col. Kramer an\nestimate of the gold reserves of the\nBank of Japan, which they said was\nJapans total reserve except for\nsmall amounts earmarked for ship\nment to Indo-China and Siam, but\nthe figure was not disclosed imme\ndiately.\nCol. Kramer previously had an\nnounced that the Finance Ministry\nestimated Japan\u2019s gold reserve at\n$125,000,000.\nThe bankers denied knowledge of\nfull details on imperial household\nfunds or where the imperial gold\ndeposits might be located, but they\ndisclosed that the household owned\napproximately 25 per cent interest\nin the Bank of Japan, and the Jap\nanese government owned a 55 per\ncent interest.\nNew Liaison Chief Named.\nMeanwhile, the newspaper Asahi\nreported that Kenji Kodama, for\nmer head of the Central China De\nvelopment Co., one of the firms\nordered Closed, had been appointed\nnew president of the central liaison\noffice, the Japanese agency that re\nceives and passes on to the proper\n(See OCCUPATION, Page A-2.)\nLaurel Results\nFIRST RACE\u2014Purse. SC,000; 2-year\nolds: claiming: ti furlongs.\nM. Longeine (Covalli) 204.50 73.00 20.20\nOne Blend (Padgett) 14.50 7.30\nLoudoun Boy (Wood) 3.00\nTime, 1:16J4.\nAlso ran\u2014Fagranny. More Flame. Ron\nLight, Magic Steo. Gimpy Girl. Jane Dale.\nSunday Knight. Chaltic and Forever At It.\nU. S. and Soviet Must Find Basis\nFor Amity, Stalin Tells Pepper\nPremier Offers Assurances 6-Billion Loan\nWould Not Be Used to Push War Production\n(Senator Pepper, Democrat, of\nFlorida, a member of the Senate\nForeign Relations Committee,\nnow on tour of the Near East,\nobtained an exclusive interview\nwith Premier Stalin in which\nhe asked the Russian leader his\nviews on domestic and foreign\naffairs.)\nBy CLAUDE D. PEPPER.\nCAIRO, Oct. 1\u2014For nearly an\nhour on the evening of September\n14 I talked with Generalissimo\nJoseph Stalin in the Kremhn. That\nis a great experience, for, as you\nsit across the table from him you\nknow you are privileged to talk with\nthe'single, most-powerful man in\nthe world\u2014the man who is going to\ndetermine in a large way what kind\nof world ours is to be.\n8talin recently was made gen\neralissimo so he is now addressed by\n\nthat rank, and not as marshal. With\nthe generalissimo* were Assistant\nCommissar for Foreign Affairs H.\nA. Y. Vyshinsky and a young in\nterpreter whom I had known when\nhe had been assigned to the Soviet\nEmbassy in Washington. I was ac\ncompanied by Mr. George F. Ken\nnan, American charge d\u2019affaires\nhere, who interpreted for me.\nThe generalissimo wore his Red\nArmy uniform with a single decora\ntion just over his heart. His man\nner is modest and without affecta\ntion. He usually is doodling\u2014draw\ning figures on a writing pad\u2014while\nwaiting for his remarks to be trans\nlated. Generally he sits very quietly\nand speaks in a low voice with a\nlittle animation, but when a subject\nof keen Interest to him is raised\nhis large, brown eyes light up, his\nface becomes alive and full of ex\npression, and he speaks emphatical\n(See STALIN, Page A-14.)\nW*mm\nP] 'pi mwmm\nl||| ^WELL...THAT'S THE\nll!|l WAY THE COURT'S\nHEADING*\nf i A\nTruman Visits Court\nTo See Burton Take\nOath a< Justice\nAttendance Is Record\nFor 155-Year History\nOf Supreme Tribunal\nBy the Associate^ Presa.\nPresident Truman made an\nunprecedented visit to the Su\npreme Court today to see his\nfirst appointee, Harold H. Bur\nton, Ohio Republican, sworn in\nas an associate justice.\nVeteran court officials said that\nin the court\u2019s 155-year history no\nPresident had appeared in the court\nroom while serving as Chief Exec\nutive.\nMr. Truman stepped into the yel\nlow marble courtroom from a side\nentrance eight minutes before the\nblack-robed justices marched to\ntheir bench at noon.\nCourt attaches escorted Mr. Tru\nman to a mahogany counsel table\ndirectly beneath the bar and a. few\nfeet from Chief Justice Stone. Prom\nthis point in front of the jammed\ncourtroom he had an unobstructed\nview of the brief ceremony by which\nMr. Burton, with whom the Presi\ndent served in the Senate, became\na member of the high tribunal.\nMany Senators also were present.\nChats With Attorney General.\n_ _._i. --1- _ a rpu n V*\nHit VUUi IliatOWHt) WWUMW\nWaggaman, clapped his hands\nsharply and commanded, \u201crise\u201d as\nMr. Truman entered the chamber.\nThe President, wearing a gray,\ndouble-breasted suit and soft collar\nshirt, chatted with Attorney General\nClark and other acquaintances while\nawaiting for the justices to appear.\nMr. Truman stopped chatting and\njumped to his feet quickly at the\ninstant Chief Justice Stone appeared\nthrough the velvet curtain leading\nto the bench. He exchanged smiles\nwith the justices as they took their\nplaces.\nJustice Stone paid a tribute to\nOwen J. Roberts, who retired from\nthe court last July and whom Jus\ntice Burton succeeds. Then, Mr\nBurton, wearing the traditional\nblack silk judicial robe for the first\ntime, stepped to the d,esk of Charles\nElmore Cropley, clerk of the court.\nWith upraised right hand he swore\nto give justice to all impartially.\nAfter Justice Burton took his seat,\nthe President left. He was in the\ncourtroom 13 minutes.\nJustice Burton already had taken\nan oath to support the Constitution.\nIt was administered by Justice Stone\nin the court\u2019s conference room.\nMr. Truman's appointment of the\n(See BURTON, Page <-5.)\nIrving Berlin Gets\nMedal for Merit\nFrom Marshall\nIrving Berlin, song writer of two\nwars and author of \u201cThis Is the\nArmy,\u201d the all-Army musical which\npoured more than (9,000,000 into the\nArmy Emergency Relief Fund, was\npresented the Medal for Merit today\nby Gen. George C. Marshall, Army\nChief of Staff.\nThe medal was awarded at the\ndirection of President Truman in\nrecognition of Mr. Berlin\u2019s \u201chighly\nmeritorious service\u201d since February,\n1942.\nMr. Berlin voluntarily gave his\ntime, the facilities of his organiza\ntions \u201cand the earnings of his genius\nfor the benefit of Army emergency\nrelief all without remuneration,\u201d the\nArmy said.\n\u201cI shall always feel deeply grati\nfied for all your efforts,\u201d- Gen. Mar\nshall said, in presenting the medal\nto the song writer.\nMr. Berlin stood at attention as\nMaj. Gen. Edward F. Witsell, act\ning adjutant general, read the cita\ntion. His wife was a witness at\nthe ceremony.\nHenry McLemore\nIs Back\nHenry McLemore, whose\nhumorous column was enjoyed\nby thousands of Star readers\nbefore the draft took him into\nthe Army, has been discharged\nand has resumed writing.\nThe first of his postwar col\numns appears today on Page\nA-8.\nHigh Unemployment Forecast\nThroughout 7946 by Snyder\nReconversion Chief Stresses Shock\nIn Postwar Release of 18 Million\nReconversion Director Snyder\npredicted today in a report to\nPresident Truman and Congress\nthat \u201chigh unemployment will\npersist through 1946.\u201d\nWithin that period 18,000,000 per\nsons will be released from combat\nservice and war production \u201ca\nshock to our economy\u201d\u2014Mr. Snyder\nsaid, and several million who have\nheld jobs will retire from the labor\nmarket. But demobilization of the\narmed services will Increase the ci\nvilian working force by 5.000,000, be\nwarned, and industry cannot take\nup this slack as fast a military per\nsonnel will be reduced. He repeated\nan earlier estimate of 8,000,000 Idle\nby spring.\nThe 48-page report, Mr. Snyder\u2019s\nfourth, was labeled \"Three Keys to\nReconversion. Production, Jobs,\nMarkets.\u201d\nThe reconversion chief said there\nis likely to be a market for more\ndurable goods than can be made\u2014\nsuch as automobiles\u2014in the im\nmediate future, and that the same\nis true of nondurable goods.\nHowever, he explained, the time\nnecessarily involved in organizing\nthe flow of durable goods produc\ntion will hold down employment in\nthis segment of the economy. This\nrestriction on buying power, he said,\nwill be reflected in additional job\nlessriess in the consumer goods in\ndustries, where supply is not a\nlimiting factor.\nIn this connection, he re-empha\n(See SNYDER, Page A-2.)\nTruman Asked to Hold\nAtomic Secrets Until\nBoard Is Appointed\nHouse Subcommittee\nMakes Request After\nInspecting World Bases\nMembers of the House Sub\ncommittee on War Department\nAppropriations, who have Just\ncompleted a world tour of mili\ntary installations, told President\nTruman today the secret of the\natomic bomb should not be re\nleased until a commission had\nbeen creatfed to study all phases\nof atomic power and submitted\nits findings.\nShortly after the group left the\nWhite House, it was announced Mr.\nTruman\u2019s message to Congress on\nthe subject, which earlier had been\npromised \"in a few days,\u201d would\nbe issued this week.\nThe subcommittee\u2019s views were in\ncorporated in a statement embody\ning nine \u201cconclusions\u201d which were\npresented to the President this\nA Iffv Tmimnn'e\nj reaction, Chairman Snyder said \"he\ndidn\u2019t get mad.\u201d\nUrges Immediate Action.\nThe congressional group, which\nwas gone 39 days, also had pointed\ncomment on foreign countries seek\ning supplies and credit.\n\u201cThere is a worldwide tendency to\nregard the United States as a coun\ntry of unlimited wealth, \u201cthe state\nment said.\u201d We should say frankly\nto every country taking aid, that\nhere as there, wealth is produced\nonly by work and if supplies or cred\nits are furnished, beyond minimum\nfood or clothing, repayment must be\nassured.\u201d\nTne subcommittee recalled it had\nhandled the appropriation for the\natomic bomb project and recom\nmended that the suggetsed commis\nsion should be set up immediately.\nIt was proposed the group be com\nposed of scientists who directed the\nproject, the joint chiefs of staff,\nthe State Department and mem\nbers of Congress.\nWould Use Aviation Network.\nOther recommendations included:\nRetaining possession of enemy is\nlands in the Pacific; surplus war\nstocks in every foreign country\nshould be sold immediately or ex\nchanged for the best values that can\nbe obtained to avoid depredation\nLegion Raps Bradley\nFor Reputed Plan to\nShift Control of Loans\nAdministrator Denies\nHe Expressed Opinion\nOn Transfer Proposal\nAfter only six weeks as admin\nistrator of veterans\u2019 affairs, Gen.\nOmar N. Bradley faced his first\ncriticism today\u2014from the Amer\nican Legion, which has consist\nently \u201cplayed ball\u201d with the Vet\nerans\u2019 Administration.\nThe Legion charged Gen. Bradley\nhas proposed shifting some Veterans\u2019\nAdministration functions\u2014particul\narly home loans under the GI Bill\nof Rights\u2014to other Geovernment\nagencies.\nGen. Bradley promptly said he had\nmade no such proposal and has ex\npressed no opinion on whether the\nloans should be transferred.\nExpressed No Opinion.\n\u201cI have talked with various\ngroups,\u201d Gen. Bradley said. \u201cMr.\nJohn Thomas Taylor (American\nLegion legislative director) was in\nnna rtf fhrtca oTAimc T tollrpd with\nbankers and insurance men who\nwere at a meeting. My purpose was\nto find out the view of financial peo\nple on the handling of these loans.\nI, myself, made no proposal and ex\npressed no opinion.\u201d\nThe Legion, which pointed out it\nsponsored the GI bill, announced\nIt would fight any transfers \u201cto the\nlimit.\u201d Mr. Taylor said Gen. Brad\nley made the proposal at a confer\nence between Veterans\u2019 Adminis\ntration officials, lending agencies\nand Legion representatives.\nThe Legion told Gen. Bradley\nthat \u201cif it is logical to transfer\u201d\nhome loans to the FHA, \u201cit would be\njust as logical to transfer veterans\nhospitalization to the United States\nPublic Health Service. Like\nwise, it would be just as logical\nto transfer the payment of pensions\nand compensation to the Social\nSecurity Board; veterans\u2019 insurance\nto the Treasury Department and so\non until nothing is left of the Vet\nerans\u2019 Administration as it is pres\nently constituted.\u201d\nCongress Rejected Plan.\nThe Legion said that when the\nGI bill was discussed in Congress, it\nwas proposed that FHA administer\nthe home loans but that the pro\nposal was rejected because FHA\n(See ATOMIC, Page A-2.)\n(See BRADLEY. Page A-2.)\nLoss of 50 Billion Seen in Sale\nOf War Surplus Costing 60\nBy tnc Associated press.\nFederal officials expect a loss of\nat least $50,000,000,000 in sale and\ndisposal of America\u2019s surplus war\ngoods.\nThis estimate was disclosed today\nby Chariman Manasco of the House\nExpenditures Committees which is\ndrafting legislation aimed at im\nproving disposal methods.\nMr. Manasco told a reporter he\nhad been checking for some time\nwith officials in charge of sales and\nsummarized his findings this way:\n\u201cOur surplus war goods are eval\nuated at somewhere between $60,\n000.000,000 and *100,000,000,000, de\npending on whether you figure the\namount at cost or at supposed\nworth.\n\u201cBecause much of this material\nis either overseas, or obsolete, or\nboth, it is expected that we will\nonly realize about *10,000,000,000 on\nits suit.\n\"That leaves at least *50,000,000,\n000 the American taxpayers won\u2019t\nbe able to write off the national\ndebt.\"\nMr. Manasco added, however,\nthat he believed a heavy loss on\nthe goods should be accepted by\nthe public as a \u201ccost of war.\"\nmi\nUMW Aide Sees\nWes) Virginia\nCoal Shutdown\nStrike of 108,000\n'Within Few Days'\nHeld Possible\nBULLETIN.\nCHARLESTON, W. Va. UP)\u2014\nA complete shutdown of West\nVirginia\u2019s bituminous coal in\ndustry, employing approxi\nmately 108,000 men, is possible\n\u201cwithin the next few days,\u201d a\nUnited Mine Workers official\ndeclared today as the mine\nforemen\u2019s strike spread to\nsouthern counties. William\nBlizzard, vice president of\nUMW district 17, reported\nthat 43 mines failed to operate\ntoday in the area because of\nthe walkout of foremen seek\ning recognition of their union.\nWORKERS\u2019 COMMITTEE to de\ncide tonight on Amoco strike here.\nPage B-l\nBy the Associated Tress.\nTune was running out today;\nfor settlement of the oil wag*\ncontroversy as critical new de\nvelopments dragged the tele\nphone and bituminous coal in\ndustries into strike-danger zones.\nThis was the general picture:\n1. Oil\u2014the stage was nearing\nwhere Secretary of Labor Schwellen\nbach said spreading strikes of mor*\nthan 36,000 CIO oil workers would\nperil Army and Navy operations.\nGovernment action\u2014with seizure of\nthe struck refineries as a last resort\n\u2014drew that much closer. At issue is\nthe union\u2019s demand for a 30 per\ncent wage increase. The strikes\nhave spread into eight States.\nConference Resumed.\nWage conferences between union\nand management officials were to\nresume this morning /following\nday-long session yesterday at which\n$5.36 Collect Wire\nFrom Schwellenbach\nIrks CIO Official\nBy the Associated Press.\nDETROIT, Oct. 1.\u2014August\nScholle, CIO director in Mich\nigan, frowned today over a\nfive-page-long telegram from\nSecretary of Labor Schwellen\nbach.\nThe telegram was in refer\nence to the oil workers strike.\n\u201cSchwellenbach sent it col\nlect,\u201d Mr. Scholle said. \u201cIt\ncost me $5.36. How would you\nfeel about something like that?\u201d\nno prospects of immediate agree\nment were produced. Mr. Schwellen\nbach was reported to be preparing\na fresh appeal for settlement.\nOne minor break came early to\nday when two small Detroit plants\nsigned with the union for a wage in\ncrease of 17 !s cents an hour. The\nnumber of workers involved was\nsmall, however.\nOn November 1, when the re\nfineries switch from a 48-hour to\na 40-hour week, an additional in\ncrease of 35 cents hourly will be\ncome effective.\nThe 35-cent boost. Mr. Knight\nsaid, would provide the 30 per cent\nincrease which the union seeks na\ntionally.\nLewis\u2019 Second Bid Rejected.\n2. Soft coal\u2014Operators turned\ndown for a second time an invita\ntion from John L. Lewis to meet\nwith him. The purpose would be\ntalks about recognizing Mr. Lewis\u2019\nforemen\u2019s union, already striking in\nWest Virginia and Pennsylvania.\nTelling Mr. Lewis he first should\nget the strikers back to work, the op\nerators contended the United Mine\nWorkers\u2019 chief was violating hi*\ncontract \"by conducting an illegal\nstrike.\u201d\nWhether Mr. Lewis now would ask\nthe 400,000 bituminous miners to\nback up the supervisory unit became\nan immediate concern of Govern\nment labor officials.\n3. Telephone\u2014A brief \u201cdemon\nstration\u201d work stoppage by 200,000\nmembers of the National Federa\ntion of Telephone Workers was con\nsidered a \u201cdefinite possibility\u201d by\nPresident Joseph Beirne. He said\nso as he called an Executive Board\nmeeting in New York to discuss a\ntentative National Labor Relations\nBoard order. It recommended dis\nestablishment of the federation\u2019s af\nfiliate, the Western Electric Em\nployes\u2019 Association, in New York and\nNew Jersey areas.\nThe report ordered dissolution of\n(See LABOR, Page A-5.)\nArmored Car Guard\nKilled Foiling Holdup\nBy the Associated Press.\nDETROIT, Oct. 1.\u2014A guard on\nan armored car was shot to death\nin front of a downtown bank early\ntoday when he resisted efforts of a\nlone gunman to hold up the vehicle.\nThe guard, William Hill of De\ntroit, was standing near the open\nrear door of the car when the ban\ndit approached with gun in hand\nand shouted, \u201cThis is a stickup.\u201d\nMr. Hill, police said, reached for\nhis own gun and the bandit opened\nfire. He fled as the guard dropped\nto the street and pedestrians scur\nried for cover.\nTwo other armored car drivers,\nwho had stopped for a traffic sig\nnal, chased after the gunman, ex\nchanging shots for two blocks.\nPolice said the gunman fired one\nshot at his pursuers while they\npoured nine shots at him before\nfelling him with a bullet in the\ngroin.\nThe man, identified by police as\nRichard Ruff, 22, attempted to flea\nagain, but the guards, Luther Lord,\n47, and Johnny Schauer, 47, closed\nin on him and beat him to the\nground with their pistol butts.\nHe was removed to receiving hos\npital, where his condition was re\nported as \u201cfair.**","height":"31384","width":"22424"}}
